{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"aef73a17-7b50-4bf0-a102-322e96b476f0","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"tooluse_vxxtHkfiubKebTLISLU2E6","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"dotnet --version 2>/dev/null || echo \"dotnet not installed\"","description":"Check .NET SDK version","initial_wait":10},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Check .NET SDK version"}],"interactionId":"0dc4416c-1817-4010-bee2-3b14c8619db7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer reports that `dotnet build` CLI builds are slow for incremental builds (2-4 seconds even when nothing changed), while Visual Studio rebuilds nearly instantly. They've already ruled out analyzers and confirmed incremental targets work.\n\nThe key insight here is the difference between how VS and the CLI invoke MSBuild:\n\n1. **Visual Studio** uses a long-lived MSBuild server process (the \"design-time build\" host). MSBuild stays warm in memory, so the project graph is already evaluated, and NuGet restore results are cached in-process.\n\n2. **`dotnet build` from CLI** spawns a new `dotnet` process each time, which means:\n   - .NET runtime JIT startup\n   - MSBuild node startup\n   - Re-evaluation of the project file and all imports\n   - NuGet restore check (implicit restore)\n\nSo the fix is straightforward: skip the implicit restore with `--no-restore` when packages haven't changed, and enable the MSBuild server to keep the process warm between builds. The server can be activated via an environment variable or a project setting.\n\nFor the inner loop, `dotnet watch` keeps everything running and rebuilds only what changed. I should also check if the graph-based build flag helps with incremental no-op builds, and I need to verify which .NET SDK version is in use to see if MSBuild server mode is available.","outputTokens":555,"requestId":"1C55:2E56AC:B20867:CED464:69F3FA0C"},"id":"63892a55-f820-4fd2-ace9-99cdb03b1bc9","timestamp":"2026-05-01T00:55:54.387Z","parentId":"885194ea-9b83-4c69-9f1a-5c1be8a1cdc1"}
