{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"10ba5076-8349-4520-b24a-22fdac117af8","content":"Here's the diagnosis and recommendations:\n\n## Root Cause\n\nThe project and code are fine — the bottleneck is **MSBuild process startup overhead**. Every `dotnet build` invocation spawns a new process, JITs MSBuild, re-evaluates the project graph, and runs an implicit NuGet restore. Visual Studio avoids this by keeping a long-lived MSBuild server in memory.\n\n## Recommendations (highest impact first)\n\n### 1. Skip implicit restore with `--no-restore`\nWhen packages haven't changed, this eliminates the restore phase:\n```\ndotnet build --no-restore\n```\n\n### 2. Enable the MSBuild Server\nThis keeps an MSBuild process alive between builds (like VS does), avoiding repeated JIT and project evaluation:\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\ndotnet build\n```\nOr set it permanently in the `.csproj`:\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <MSBuildServer>true</MSBuildServer>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### 3. Use `dotnet watch` for edit-build-test loops\nKeeps the host process warm and rebuilds on file changes:\n```\ndotnet watch run\n```\n\n### 4. Combine for best results\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\ndotnet build --no-restore\n```\n\nThe MSBuild server alone should cut your no-op build from **2–4s down to under 1s**, since it eliminates the JIT/startup and project re-evaluation costs that account for most of the overhead.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0dc4416c-1817-4010-bee2-3b14c8619db7","outputTokens":379,"requestId":"1C32:262BA4:B7A538:D47F13:69F3FA1C"},"id":"79ffec51-7a11-41ba-86e6-411a3e414d70","timestamp":"2026-05-01T00:56:06.841Z","parentId":"b2bde80d-447d-4f93-92ae-ec88db839297"}
